questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice is experiencing gradual memory leaks and eventually `OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`. The service uses a custom metadata cache to optimize database lookups, designed using a `WeakHashMap` to allow garbage collection of unused keys. Below is the simplified code:

java
public class MetadataCache {
    private final Map<UserKey, UserValue> cache = Collections.synchronizedMap(new WeakHashMap<>());

    public void put(String id, String role) {
        UserKey key = new UserKey(id);
        UserValue value = new UserValue(key, role);
        cache.put(key, value);
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue in a Spring Boot application where updates to a JPA entity's custom lazy-loaded collection (e.g., `PersistentBag` from Hibernate) are intermittently throwing `LazyInitializationException` or failing to commit within a `@Transactional` boundary. The simplified code is as follows:

java
@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    public void processUser(Long id) {
        User user = userRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
        updateRoles(user);
    }

    @Transactional
    public void updateRoles(User user) {
        user.getRoles().add("ROLE_ADMIN");
    }
}
